#!/usr/bin/env python3
"""Worldbook: new "Countries" reference layer - a clean, current, non-political base map.
Every country gets a muted pastel/powder color such that no two countries sharing a land
border ever share a color (computed offline via shapely: buffer-touch adjacency test +
DSATUR graph coloring, load-balanced across an 18-color pastel palette for variety rather
than collapsing to the theoretical 4-color minimum), plus its name set across it like a
classroom atlas (label anchor = pole-of-inaccessibility-style point via grid refinement,
not a naive centroid that can fall outside concave/archipelago shapes; text size scales
with sqrt(country area), clamped to a readable range). Color here carries no data - the
new legend branch says so explicitly, matching the project's "color = information, never
decoration" rule for every other layer.
Idempotent, pure ASCII source (the baked JSON payloads are emitted with ensure_ascii=True,
so every non-ASCII glyph is already a backslash-u escape).
Usage: python3 worldbook_countries_layer.py index.html index.html
"""
import sys

INP = sys.argv[1] if len(sys.argv) > 1 else "index.html"
OUT = sys.argv[2] if len(sys.argv) > 2 else "index.html"
text = open(INP, encoding="utf-8").read()

